properties.Name: Viking
properties.website: The Viking resource play is a shallower Cretaceous porous sandstone conglomerate in eastern and central Alberta spanning northwest from Redwater though Provost and into the Dodsland area of west central Saskatchewan.  Conventional production from the Viking started in the 1950’s and the play has been delineated by more than 8000 vertical wells.  Like the Cardium, the Viking is a shallow, low risk light oil play in comparison to deeper resource plays.  Like the Bakken, the Viking is a light sweet crude with 35-39 API.

properties.Name: Haynesville / Bossier
properties.website: The Haynesville / Bossier play currently covers about 10,000 square miles, centered upon Shelby County, Texas and De Soto Parish, Louisiana.  The Haynesville is a shale of the Upper Jurassic age found between the Cotton Valley and Smackover.  Most of the southern half of the Haynesville area is overlain by the Bossier Shale, which is also a prolific gas play and which may well extend beyond the Haynesville in a southwesterly direction.  In addition to the prolific gas production within the play, recent completion activities shows early signs of success for oil production in the Travis Peak.

properties.Name: Duverney
properties.website: The Duverney shale fairway extends from Southeast to Northwest in the greater Pembina -Kaybob Region of Alberta.  The Duverney is rich organic shale of Devonian aged formation that is significantly deeper than other shale targets currently being developed in the Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin.   Since 2009, billions of dollars have been spent at crown land sales as the Duverney contains significant amounts of liquids rich hydrocarbons including oil and free condensate in addition to shale gas.  Production rates have been prolific making the Duverney one of North America’s most attractive liquids rich plays rivaling similar unconventional plays such as the Eagle Ford Shale in Texas.

properties.Name: Bakken / Lower Shaunavon
properties.website:
The Bakken shale is a Late Devonian Early Missisipian formation comprised by three distinct layers. The upper and lower have non-porous rock, while the middle layer has the features of a conventional oil bearing reservoir. Geographically, the Bakken is located in the Williston Basin extending from Eastern Saskatchewan down through North Dakota. Recent discoveries in Alberta and Montana have extended the play and producers in Alberta now refer to the Bakken as the Alberta Bakken Shale or Exshaw Bakken Play. Bakken Oil is high quality sweet crude with API ranges between 42 and 47 API.
The Lower Shaunavon is a Bathonian aged member composed of sandstone, limestone or dolomite. Located in southern Saskatchewan, this oil is rated as medium crude with gravity ranges between 18 to 22 API. Prior to new horizontal and fracturing technologies, this reservoir was not considered economic.

properties.Name: Cardium
properties.website: The Cardium is an upper cretaceous aged sandstone/shale formation located in Alberta and extends up into Eastern British Columbia near Dawson Creek and down to the Canada-U.S. border.  The Pembina Oil field which is the largest in Alberta is located in the Cardium Shale Formation and was first discovered in 1953.  Natural gas is primarily produced from the Cardium formation in the foothills around the Athabasca River-Edson area while oil is produced in the central Alberta region.  The Cardium is generally a shallow low risk light oil play in an area of well-developed infrastructure which reduces costs for producers.

properties.Name: Eagle Ford / Woodbine
properties.website: The Eagle Ford / Woodbine play currently covers about 33,000 miles, running from Webb and Maverick counties along the border with Mexico in a North Easterly direction as far as Jasper and San Augustine counties. Known as a 'Shale' but more of a carbonate, the Eagle Ford has long been acknowledged as the source rock for other hydrocarbon formations, most notably the Austin Chalk.  It is the primary objective in the southwestern 40% of the play.  The Eaglebine is a term coined recently to describe the area where both the Eagle Ford and the Woodbine can be targeted in a coordinated effort; this covers the central 20% of the play.  The northeastern 40% of the play is where the Woodbine (an upper cretaceous oil bearing sand) becomes the primary objective.  This area also exhibits good secondary and tertiary objectives including the Eagle Ford, Glen Rose, Travis Peak, Cotton Valley and the Bossier sands.

properties.Name: Marcellus
properties.website: The Marcellus play currently covers about 55,000 square miles, including southwestern New York, most of western Pennsylvania, most of West Virginia and a small part of east central Ohio. It is a Hamilton group shale of the Middle Devonian epoch, within the Paleozoic era, for much of its areal extent it can be found between the Mahantango and the Onondaga formations.

properties.Name: Utica
properties.website: The Utica play currently covers about 95,000 square miles, including southwestern New York, western & northern Pennsylvania, most of West Virginia, eastern Ohio and small areas within Kentucky, Virginia and Tennessee. It is calcareous black shale of the late Ordovician epoch, for much of its areal extent it can be found between the Oswego formation and the Trenton / Black River limestone.
